Negative Interest Club
Brussels—For most of the past decade, central banks have only made limited progress in containing the powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has maintained interest rates at zero, and has carried out unprecedented asset purchases through large-scale bond-buying operations.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have all followed the Fed's lead, implementing their own versions of the so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not been boosted anywhere in a reasonable manner.
Despite these countries struggling with deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performances — are increasingly diverging.
The US and the UK's current growth is strong enough to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the euro area and Japan are doubling down on QE, pushing long-term policy rates further into the negative interval.
What is the reason for this difference?
It can be briefly answered by debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had chronic fiscal deficits and thus have been debtor nations, whereas the euro area and Japan have had external surpluses and thus have been creditor nations.
Negative interest rates are beneficial to debtors but detrimental to creditors. Therefore, after the global economic crisis, the introduction of negative interest rates stimulated the recovery of the United States and the United Kingdom, but had little effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
Until now, most creditor countries in the world, including countries with large persistent current account surpluses such as Denmark and Switzerland, have negative interest rates, not only long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also medium-term bonds.
This is not a good thing.
Although the low interest rates have little effect, central banks of these economies still insist on this policy.
If you proposed that lowering interest rates or quantitative easing (QE) is impossible to bring benefits to the economy, they would talk around it, refuting the concept that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — — which looks unassailable on the surface.
But actually, it's full of holes.
The foundation of economics courses also mention the peculiar phenomenon of the 'backwards-bending savings supply curve': in a certain environment, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because a decrease in interest rates reduces the income of savers, they will reduce their spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
All of these are not denying the general rule — — it's the foundation of modern monetary policy — — lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
Only the impact is different due to the different debt status of the economy.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors will naturally be more than debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effect of the interest rate floor monetary policy is different in the creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were usually small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly because of the leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage is still continuing to increase at the national level.
Although the overall balance of trade has been somewhat alleviated since the financial crisis, it has not been reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor status, and differentiate from deficit economies.
Some major commodity-exporting countries, like Russia and Saudi Arabia, have huge current account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them the main exceptions to the differentiation of foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, the world oil price has plunged, reversing the trend of these countries' wealth.
Their export earnings have dramatically decreased, many countries have seen a drop of over 50%, forcing them to run deficits and rely on their massive sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodity boom.
It is now unavoidable to sharply reduce spending.
Industrialized economies face totally different challenges.
They're problems — — from a certain point of view, are a luxury problem — — to ensure consumers spend the unexpected windfall obtained from the decline in import prices.
But in debtor countries, negative interest rates seem not to have advanced this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This differentiation also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole, the eurozone is a debtor economy, there are also countries with debt.
Debt economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now all have frequent projects with surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But the current trade surplus of traditional debt countries is too high, causing the debt country/debt holder asymmetry to continue increasing.
The most worth noting is that since the financial crisis broke out, Germany's current account surplus has increased to near 8% of GDP, indicating that Germany has accumulated more surplus during this period than the total of the previous historical record.
Following the current trend, Germany's creditor position may increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
The central bank governor should be patient.
Actually, economists support the global trend of central bank independence because the central bank governor tends to be less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to have little patience, for low inflation is causing them a great headache, despite output gap slowly being filled, and the US and Japan have achieved full employment.
Debt country central bank governors must stop manipulating the economy with more currency easing that may not be beneficial to production.
Instead, they should allow the economy to recover itself, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
Recently, ECB governor Draghi admitted that in today's global environment, the current monetary policy stance may not be effective.
But promising more of the same old policies is not the solution.
